^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That is not how I play it Gail. Although you don't have to have a good hand you certainly could. Surely you do you want Irene to pass with 10 points. Let me expand this issue further. First, let me define a couple of terms.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|"Responder", as you know, is the term we use for the partner of the opener. Similarly, "advancer" is the term we use for the partner of an overcaller. So the partner of the ^*Bopener^*N is the ^*Bresponder^*N and partner of ^*Bovercaller^*N is the ^*Badvancer^*N. And the rules for taking a bid by an ^*Badvancer^*N is slightly different.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One general problem I see some of my students have is they feel that advancer has to have a stronger hand than responder to take the same actions. That is not really the case. It is true that, unlike responder, who must bid with 6+ points if there is a pass after an opening bid, advancer does not have the same obligation. Advancer, without 3+ card support, can pass with even some relatively strong hands (up to 9 or even a bad 10/his defensive cards) even when there is a pass after partner's overcall.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, it is also true that bids by advancer are somewhat similar to bids by responder. So a new suit at the 1-level can be done with as few as 6 or 7 points and a new suit at the 2 level only promises 10 points. However, one difference between responder and advancer is that ^*Ba new suit by advancer is almost always a 5-card suit^*N.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also, I play that, just like a new suit by responder is forcing, a new suit by advancer is also forcing. Some experts play new suits by advancer are not forcing (and hence cue bids are the only forcing bid that advancer can make and do not necessarily show support), but I think that is wrong and often creates unnecessarily difficult bidding problems for advancer. So I very much recommend you play a new suit by advancer is forcing.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Again I like to emphasize that  regardless of point count if you have 9 or less LOTT is your main guide in deciding how high to bid. With support and 10+ you can cue bid. I tend to prefer that a cue bid shows 4-card support, as I think uncovering a 9-card fit is very important. So, with 3-card support and 10+ I will usually bid a new suit if possible, and only cue bid with 3-card support if I have no other good bid available. |
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On the other hand, if you want to play that a cue bid only promises 3-card support, that is a reasonable way to play. Or if you want to use both 2NT and cue bids to differentiate between 3-card and 4-card support, that is fine as well.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On another point as an advancer, I will not necessarily bid 1NT with 8-9 unless I have a stopper in the opponents' suit(s) and at least a doubleton in partner's suit. As I said above, you can pass with as much as 9 and should do so unless you have a reason to bid. |
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Reasons to bid include: 
showing a good suit of your own, 
showing a stopper in the opponent's suit, or, most importantly,
showing partner you have support for his suit. 
Also a bid of 2N can be made with 11-14. You can bid 3N with 15+.|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As I mentioned above, change of suit by advancer shows the same values as if made by responder. That is change of suit at the 1 level can be made with as little as 6 or 7 points (although if you are weak you should have a good and/or long suit) and change of suit at the 2 level can be done with as little as 10. And change of suit shows a 5+ card suit.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|After a takeout double my teaching maintains, any bid other than redouble and 2NT (Jordan) denies 10 points. However, just so you know, it is more common to play that bids at the 1-level over a takeout double are forcing -- they only promise 6 points but can be made with 10 or more points. But bids at the 2-level deny 10 points. I find that very counter-intuitive which is why I recommend my style of redoubling and 2N as the only way to show 10+ points and make a forcing bid.|
