^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First let me discuss the opening lead. Normally it is not a good idea to lead a suit the opponents bid. It was ok for West to not lead a diamond. But with KQJ a diamond lead has merit given it is a minor suit. If North had bid a major, and I held KQJ of that major I would not lead the suit regardless, because I know that is North's long suit. |
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But in a minor you have a bit more latitude (although most of the time (80%+) the opener has at least 4 cards in their minor). Therefore, it is fine that Irene chose not to lead a diamond. A club lead is a little risky, but given it is the unbid suit, a reasonable choice. However, the Jack promises the 10 or a doubleton. So given she chose to lead a club, the @C6 is the correct lead. Here it turns out not to matter but it could.|
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next is the bidding. There is some case to be made to open light in 3rd seat because given 2 passes, it is likely 4th seat has an opener. It turns out, after 2 passes, the average HCP holding between the 2 passers is about 16 HCP. Therefore, on average, 3rd and 4th seat will hold 24 HCP. Thus, in 3rd seat, say you have a 10 count that means it is likely 4th seat has around 14. So if you want to make it more difficult for them to bid, you could make a case for opening light. |
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, I see little point in opening a 1 bid light (especially 1 of a minor). But I do see a good case for preempting, even opening a weak 2 with a 5-card suit and a singleton or void because that means 4th seat has to start bidding at the 2 or 3 level. After all is said and done, in third seat I recommend very aggressive preempts, especially not vul but not light opening 1 bids.|
PG| ***** 71 ***** |


NT|^B@2
BabsG:  Howard - in this auction is the 1@H by passed hand forcing?|
PG| ***** 72 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Since I am a passed hand 1@H is not forcing. However, I do play, assuming you play 2/1, that 1N is still forcing over 1 of a major because sometimes with a 1N hand you have a 3-card limit raise or a long suit of your own that you want to play in. So although many experts play 1N by a passed hand as semi-forcing, I play it as forcing.|
